{"text": "====== [10.2] The classical equations of motion\n\nIf \u02c6x is the location of a particle, then its rate of change is called velocity. By the rate of change formula we identify\n\nthe velocity operator v as follows:\n\n\u02c6v\n\n=\n\ni[ \u02c6H, \u02c6x]\n\n=\n\ni\n\n\u0014 1\n\n2m(\u02c6p \u2212A(\u02c6x))2, \u02c6x\n\n\u0015\n\n=\n\n1\n\nm(\u02c6p \u2212A(x))\n\n(10.9)\n\nand we have:\n\nd\u27e8\u02c6x\u27e9\n\ndt\n\n= \u27e8\u02c6v\u27e9,\n\n3D:\n\n\u02c6x := (\u02c6x, \u02c6y, \u02c6z),\n\n\u02c6v := (\u02c6vx, \u02c6vy, \u02c6vz)\n\n(10.10)\n\nIt is useful to relaize that the kinetic part of the Hamiltonian can be written as (1/2)m\u02c6v2. The commutaion relations\n\nof the velocity components are\n\n[m\u02c6vi, m\u02c6vj]\n\n=\n\ni(\u2202iAj \u2212\u2202jAi)\n\n=\n\ni\u03b5ijkBk\n\n(10.11)\n\n[V (\u02c6x), m\u02c6vj]\n\n=\n\ni \u2202jV (\u02c6x)\n\n(10.12)\n\nThe rate of change of the velocity \u02c6v is called acceleration. By the rate of change formula\n\nd\u27e8\u02c6v\u27e9\n\ndt\n\n=\n\ni\n\n\u00141\n\n2m\u02c6v2 + V (\u02c6x), \u02c6v\n\n\u0015\n\n+ \u2202\u02c6v\n\n\u2202t\n\n=\n\n1\n\nm\n\n1\n\n2(v \u00d7 B \u2212B \u00d7 v) + E\n\n(10.13)\n\nNote that this is dense vector-style writing of 3 equations, for the rate of change of \u27e8\u02c6vx\u27e9and \u27e8\u02c6vy\u27e9and \u27e8\u02c6vz\u27e9. Above we\n\nhave used the follwing notations:\n\nB = \u2207\u00d7 A\n\n(10.14)\n\nE = \u2212\u2202A\n\n\u2202t \u2212\u2207V\n\nWe would like to emphasize that the Hamiltonian is the \u201dgenerator\u201d of the evolution of the system, and therefore all\n\nthe equations of motion can be derived from it. From the above it follows that in case of a \u201dminimal\u201d wavepacket\n\nthe expectation values of \u02c6x and \u02c6v obey the classical equations approximately. The classical Lorentz force equation\n\nbecomes exact if the B and E are constants in the region where the motion takes place:\n\nd\u27e8\u02c6v\u27e9\n\ndt\n\n=\n\n1\n\nm\n\nh\n\n\u2212B0 \u00d7 \u27e8v\u27e9+ E0\n\ni\n\n(10.15)\n\n====== [10.3] Heuristic interpretation\n\nIn the expression for the acceleration we have two terms: the \u201celectric\u201d force and the \u201cmagnetic\u201d (Lorentz) force.\n\nThese forces bend the trajectory of the particle. It is important to realize that the bending of trajectories has to do\n\nwith interference and has a very intuitive heuristic explanation.", "embedding": [-0.02714366, 0.02847237, 0.03195327, 0.023520919, 0.020363266, 0.020838639, 0.0145405065, -0.02861256, -0.02082144, 0.055717707, 0.016109703, 0.028961273, -0.0004968527, -0.044179387, -0.0406658, 0.017693559, -0.010788424, -0.030800033, -0.08650804, 0.035744015, 0.017725773, 0.020557484, -0.052763224, -0.062990025, 0.0037323467, 0.017472468, 0.029926589, -0.02200378, 0.03702987, 0.067710295, 0.03917178, -0.007896133, 0.016500844, -0.024928836, -0.0121978745, 0.007940402, 0.00013856334, -0.020588176, 0.04042827, -0.05176693, 0.05775167, -0.008582845, 0.013950752, -0.008698375, -0.03716666, -0.02621396, 0.0026191769, 6.0151742e-05, -0.029587401, -0.032415863, 0.038167935, -0.014527727, 0.0036709197, -0.037506826, -0.017450899, -0.0067918207, -0.01438579, -0.0015678831, -0.0010310736, 0.057252616, 0.029223466, -0.006341845, 0.017934157, -0.05354571, -0.039270476, 0.027682435, -0.023371216, 0.01917536, 0.0101262685, -0.04833916, -0.0330892, 0.019723227, 0.03472166, 0.03528186, -0.07241247, 0.09021193, 0.0111481175, -0.02757346, -0.034924902, 0.01119053, -0.018669814, -0.020862142, -0.011846285, 0.05073013, -0.034008224, -0.016864527, 0.021785412, -0.018559614, 0.03437359, -0.022239452, 0.018629266, 0.045608103, -0.0039010395, 0.0058257417, 0.024624797, 0.043164372, -0.017528791, 0.046118684, 0.041839585, 0.0120787965, 0.00071603945, 0.05855354, -0.02098569, 0.007757308, -0.039758343, 0.06721545, 0.0018591045, 0.026737917, -0.013260943, -0.072272345, 0.019835573, 0.03471454, 0.01805829, 0.010440343, 0.010464826, 0.050789602, 0.03537681, 0.00